        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Bassett Southampton</placeName>
                    <date>Aug—5 1874</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you for your extremely kind note.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I had only a very faint hope of success, &amp; your reasons are conclusive. I have come here for rest, of which I stand much in need, &amp; dare not undertake any new work. I am also at all times very unwilling to enter on any controversy. Nevertheless I thank you cordially for your offer, which tempts me much, as I have long considered the Contemporary as the highest of our English periodicals.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Knowles had explained that he was unable to reprint an article from the <hi rend="italic">North American Review</hi> in the <hi rend="italic">Contemporary Review</hi>, of which he was the editor (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-9582.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. T. Knowles, 4 August 1874</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Knowles had asked CD to consider writing for the <hi rend="italic">Contemporary Review</hi> (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-9582.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. T. Knowles, 4 August 1874</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
